In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events mapping** on the `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` builder method in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is pausing
            })
            .OnStop(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is no longer visible
            }));
#endif

#if IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(application =>
            {
                // Runs when the app enters the background
            }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`ConfigureLifecycleEvents`** is the single entry point for all platform lifecycle hooks.
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code compile-safe.
- `AddAndroid()`/`AddiOS()` expose the native events with strongly-typed delegates (e.g., `Activity`, `UIApplication`).
- Other events are available too — `OnRestart`, `OnResume`, `WillTerminate`, etc.
- You need `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`.
